{"id":"2012.08998","submitter":"Moritz M\\\"uller","authors":"Moritz M\\\"uller","title":"Typical forcings, NP search problems and an extension of a theorem of\n  Riis","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  We define typical forcings encompassing many informal forcing arguments in\nbounded arithmetic and give general conditions for such forcings to produce\nmodels of the universal variant of relativized $T^1_2$. We apply this result to\nstudy the relative complexity of total (type 2) NP search problems associated\nto finitary combinatorial principles.\n  Complexity theory compares such problems with respect to polynomial time\nmany-one or Turing reductions. From a logical perspective such problems are\ngraded according to the bounded arithmetic theories that prove their totality.\nThe logical analogue of a reduction is to prove the totality of one problem\nfrom the totality of another. The link between the two perspectives is tight\nfor what we call universal variants of relativized bounded arithmetics. We\nstrengthen a theorem of Buss and Johnson (2012) that infers relative bounded\ndepth Frege proofs of totality from polynomial time Turing reducibility.\n  As an application of our general forcing method we derive a strong form of\nRiis' finitization theorem (1993). We extend it by exhibiting a simple\nmodel-theoretic property that implies independence from the universal variant\nof relativized $T^1_2$ plus the weak pigeonhole principle. More generally, we\nshow that the universal variant of relativized $T^1_2$ does not prove (the\ntotality of the total NP search problem associated to) a strong finitary\ncombinatorial principle from a weak one. Being weak or strong are simple\nmodel-theoretic properties based on the behaviour of the principles with\nrespect to finite structures that are only partially defined.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","c